{
  "topicId": "division-integers-primes-gcd",
  "mcqs": [
    {
      "id": "mcq-1",
      "question": "According to the Division Algorithm, for a = 67 and b = 12, the quotient q and remainder r are:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "q = 5, r = 7"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "q = 6, r = 1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "q = 5, r = 5"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "q = 4, r = 19"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "67 = 12 \u00d7 5 + 7, where 0 \u2264 7 < 12. This satisfies the Division Algorithm conditions.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-2",
      "question": "What is the GCD of 48 and 18 using Euclidean Algorithm?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "6"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "4"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "8"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "12"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "48 \u00f7 18 = 2 remainder 12; 18 \u00f7 12 = 1 remainder 6; 12 \u00f7 6 = 2 remainder 0. So GCD(48,18) = 6.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-3",
      "question": "Which of the following pairs are co-prime?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "14 and 21"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "15 and 28"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "18 and 27"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "24 and 36"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "gcd(15,28) = 1 (15 = 3\u00d75, 28 = 2\u00b2\u00d77, no common factors). Other pairs have common factors greater than 1.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-4",
      "question": "The smallest prime number is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "3"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "C",
      "explanation": "2 is the smallest and only even prime number. By definition, prime numbers are greater than 1.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-5",
      "question": "Using Bezout's Identity for gcd(12, 5), find x and y such that 12x + 5y = 1:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "x = 2, y = -5"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "x = -2, y = 5"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "x = -2, y = 5"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "x = 1, y = -2"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "Using Extended Euclidean Algorithm: 12 = 2\u00d75 + 2, 5 = 2\u00d72 + 1, then back-substitute to get 12(-2) + 5(5) = 1.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-6",
      "question": "If gcd(a,b) = 1 and a|bc, then which statement is true?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "a|c"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "a|b"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "a|bc"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "None of these"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "This is Euclid's Lemma. If a is coprime to b and divides bc, then a must divide c.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-7",
      "question": "What is the LCM of 12 and 18 if their GCD is 6?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "24"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "36"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "48"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "72"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "Using gcd(a,b) \u00d7 lcm(a,b) = a \u00d7 b: 6 \u00d7 lcm(12,18) = 12 \u00d7 18 = 216, so lcm = 216/6 = 36.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-8",
      "question": "Which of the following is NOT a prime number?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "43"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "57"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "61"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "71"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "57 = 3 \u00d7 19, so it is composite. 43, 61, and 71 have no divisors other than 1 and themselves.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-9",
      "question": "In the Euclidean Algorithm, the process stops when:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Both numbers become 1"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "One number becomes 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "The quotient becomes 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Remainder becomes 1"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "The Euclidean Algorithm terminates when the remainder becomes 0. At that point, the last non-zero remainder is the GCD.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-10",
      "question": "The prime factorization of 360 is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "2\u00b3 \u00d7 3\u00b2 \u00d7 5"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "2\u00b3 \u00d7 3\u00b2 \u00d7 5\u00b2"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2\u2074 \u00d7 3\u00b2 \u00d7 5"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "2\u00b3 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 5\u00b2"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "360 = 36 \u00d7 10 = (2\u00b2 \u00d7 3\u00b2) \u00d7 (2 \u00d7 5) = 2\u00b3 \u00d7 3\u00b2 \u00d7 5.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-11",
      "question": "What is gcd(0, 15)?",
